---
import Layout from '~/layouts/PageLayout.astro';
import DocsShell from '~/components/widgets/DocsShell.astro';
---

<Layout metadata={{ title: 'Quickstart — Aitroop Docs' }}>
  <DocsShell current="quickstart">
    <h1>Quickstart</h1>
    <p class="lead">
      In about 15 minutes you'll have a working App on your account. We'll build it the way Aitroop is meant to be
      used — by talking to the agent, not by clicking through menus. You don't need to know how to code.
    </p>

    <h2>Before you start</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>An account at <a href="https://app.aitroop.net">app.aitroop.net</a> (free to sign up).</li>
      <li>About 15 minutes.</li>
      <li>One real task you'd like to do repeatedly with AI. We'll use <strong>"research a company and write a one-page brief"</strong> as the example.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Step 1 — Sign in and open a chat</h2>
    <ol>
      <li>Go to <a href="https://app.aitroop.net">app.aitroop.net</a> and sign up or log in.</li>
      <li>On the workspace home, click <strong>+ New Chat</strong> (top-left or sidebar).</li>
      <li>A blank chat opens. Message box at the bottom, conversation area above.</li>
    </ol>

    <div class="callout">
      <strong>What you're looking at.</strong> This is the agent's workspace. It runs in an isolated sandbox per chat,
      and has access to every Skill installed in your workspace plus every Connect (OAuth integration) you've authorized.
    </div>

    <h2>Step 2 — Ask the agent to build an App</h2>
    <p>
      Aitroop has a built-in skill called <code>aitroop-app-create</code> (the <strong>App Builder</strong>). It activates
      when you ask the agent to create, build, or update an App. Type this into the chat:
    </p>

    <div class="code-block">
Create an app that researches a company and writes a one-page brief.<br/>
<br/>
The user gives me a company name and website.<br/>
The output should be a Markdown report covering:<br/>
- Business model<br/>
- Key products<br/>
- Target customers<br/>
- Recent news (last 12 months)<br/>
- Strengths and weaknesses
    </div>

    <p>Press <strong>Enter</strong>. The agent loads the App Builder skill and starts designing.</p>

    <h2>Step 3 — Answer the agent's clarifying questions</h2>
    <p>
      The App Builder asks 1–5 short questions to nail down the design. It'll look something like this:
    </p>

    <div class="code-block" style="line-height:1.7;">
<strong>Agent:</strong> A few quick questions to design this right:<br/>
<br/>
&nbsp;1. Should the company URL be required, or can users skip it<br/>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;and let me find it from the name?<br/>
&nbsp;2. Length preference — one paragraph per section, or longer?<br/>
&nbsp;3. Output language — English by default, or configurable?<br/>
&nbsp;4. Want me to add a "competitors" section?<br/>
<br/>
<strong>You:</strong> URL optional. ~3 paragraphs per section.<br/>
English only. Yes, add competitors.
    </div>

    <p>
      Answer briefly. The agent uses your answers to choose the right AppInput types, write the prompt,
      and pick the artifact format.
    </p>

    <h2>Step 4 — Review the App design</h2>
    <p>
      The agent presents the full design before saving. It will look something like this:
    </p>

    <div class="code-block" style="font-size:0.8125rem;line-height:1.7;">
<strong style="color:var(--aw-color-primary)">App: Company Brief</strong><br/>
<span style="color:var(--aw-color-text-muted)">icon: 🏢 · tags: [research, briefing]</span><br/>
<br/>
<strong>Inputs</strong>:<br/>
&nbsp;&nbsp;company_name <span style="color:var(--aw-color-text-muted)">(text, required)</span><br/>
&nbsp;&nbsp;company_url&nbsp;&nbsp;<span style="color:var(--aw-color-text-muted)">(text, optional)</span><br/>
&nbsp;&nbsp;include_competitors <span style="color:var(--aw-color-text-muted)">(boolean, default: true)</span><br/>
<br/>
<strong>Stage 1 — research_and_write</strong> <span style="color:var(--aw-color-text-muted)">(agent stage)</span><br/>
&nbsp;&nbsp;Goal: Research <span style="color:var(--aw-color-primary)">{`{{company_name}}`}</span> (<span style="color:var(--aw-color-primary)">{`{{company_url}}`}</span>)<br/>
&nbsp;&nbsp;and write a one-page brief covering business model, key<br/>
&nbsp;&nbsp;products, target customers, recent news, and strengths/<br/>
&nbsp;&nbsp;weaknesses. <span style="color:var(--aw-color-primary)">{`{{#if include_competitors}}`}</span>Include a<br/>
&nbsp;&nbsp;competitors section.<span style="color:var(--aw-color-primary)">{`{{/if}}`}</span><br/>
<br/>
<strong>Artifact</strong>: company_brief (markdown)<br/>
<br/>
<strong>Resources</strong>: skills=[web-search], connects=[]
    </div>

    <p>
      Two things to notice. First, the goal references inputs with <code>{`{{field_id}}`}</code> — that's how
      the agent's instruction gets filled in at run time. Second, the agent picked <code>web-search</code> as the
      Skill it needs.
    </p>

    <p>
      Reply to confirm or ask for changes:
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li>"Looks good, save it." → agent calls the API and saves the App.</li>
      <li>"Change company_url to required." → agent revises and re-shows the design.</li>
      <li>"Add a second stage that drafts an outreach email." → agent extends to two stages.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Step 5 — The agent saves the App</h2>
    <p>
      Once you confirm, the agent calls <code>POST /api/apps</code> behind the scenes. You'll see something like:
    </p>

    <div class="code-block" style="line-height:1.7;">
<strong>Agent:</strong> Saved. ✅<br/>
<br/>
App: <strong>Company Brief</strong><br/>
ID: app_8f4c2e<br/>
Status: ready to run<br/>
<br/>
Find it in your <strong>App library</strong> (sidebar). Want me<br/>
to test-run it on a sample company right now?
    </div>

    <h2>Step 6 — Run your App</h2>
    <ol>
      <li>Click <strong>Apps</strong> in the sidebar. You should see <strong>Company Brief</strong> at the top of the list.</li>
      <li>Click the App. The form opens with the three fields you defined.</li>
      <li>Fill in a real company (e.g., <code>company_name = "Stripe"</code>), leave the URL blank, leave competitors on.</li>
      <li>Click <strong>Run</strong>.</li>
    </ol>

    <p>
      The agent runs the stage. You'll see its plan, web searches, and the brief being written in real time.
      30–90 seconds later, the <strong>company_brief</strong> artifact appears in the right pane —
      previewable, copy-able, and downloadable as <code>.md</code> or PDF.
    </p>

    <h2>Step 7 — Iterate by editing the App</h2>
    <p>
      Don't like something about the output? Two ways to fix it:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>Quick edit.</strong> Click <strong>Edit in chat</strong> on the App page. A new chat opens
        with the App's design loaded. Tell the agent what to change ("make the brief shorter", "add a section on hiring"),
        confirm, save. The next run picks up the new version.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Direct edit.</strong> On the App page, click <strong>Edit</strong>. You see the form (inputs),
        the stage goal, and the artifact spec. Change any field, save.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <p>
      Either way, every save creates a new version. Old versions stay in the App's history — you can roll back any time.
    </p>

    <h2>Step 8 (optional) — Schedule it</h2>
    <ol>
      <li>On the App page, click <strong>Schedules → New schedule</strong>.</li>
      <li>Pick a cron — say <strong>"Every Monday at 9 AM"</strong>.</li>
      <li>Pre-fill the inputs (e.g., always research the same competitor).</li>
      <li>Pick a delivery target — email, Slack, Notion, or a webhook.</li>
      <li>Save.</li>
    </ol>
    <p>The brief now runs and gets delivered every Monday, no clicks required.</p>

    <h2>What you actually did</h2>
    <p>
      You used Aitroop's main operational loop:
    </p>
    <ol>
      <li>Told the agent what you wanted (in natural language).</li>
      <li>Answered a few clarifying questions.</li>
      <li>Confirmed the design.</li>
      <li>Got a working App you can run, share, and schedule.</li>
    </ol>

    <div class="callout">
      <strong>This loop scales.</strong> Whether it's a one-input briefing App or a five-stage outreach pipeline,
      the way you build it is the same conversation with the agent. The agent handles the JSON, the API
      calls, the validation — you just describe the work.
    </div>

    <h2>Common confusions</h2>

    <h3>"The agent didn't ask any questions, it just built the App."</h3>
    <p>That happens when your initial description was specific enough. Skip to step 4 (review) — the design is shown
    the same way, you confirm or revise.</p>

    <h3>"My App needs to read from Gmail / Drive / GitHub — what now?"</h3>
    <p>
      Those are <strong>Connects</strong> (OAuth integrations). When you tell the agent the App needs Gmail data,
      it will add the <code>google</code> Connect to <code>resources</code>. The first time you run the App, you'll
      be prompted to authorize Gmail. Authorize once, runs forever. See <a href="/docs/connects">Connects</a> for details.
    </p>

    <h3>"The form fields aren't quite right."</h3>
    <p>
      Tell the agent. "Change <code>company_name</code> to be a multiline text instead." "Add a select dropdown for tone."
      The agent updates the design and re-saves. You don't have to write JSON.
    </p>

    <h3>"How is this different from just chatting with ChatGPT?"</h3>
    <p>
      ChatGPT doesn't have <strong>persistent Apps</strong>, <strong>shared forms</strong>, or <strong>schedules</strong>.
      Every conversation starts blank. Aitroop saves the working version as an App and makes it runnable by anyone, anytime,
      with their own data — through tools you authorize.
    </p>

    <div class="next-up">
      <span class="label">Next</span>
      <a href="/docs/concepts">Core concepts — the App schema in detail</a>
    </div>
  </DocsShell>
</Layout>
